      <Value><![CDATA[# Accessibility: Building for Everyone

Web accessibility isn't just a nice-to-have feature—it's a fundamental requirement for creating inclusive digital experiences. As I build this blog, accessibility has been a core consideration.

## Why Accessibility Matters

Accessibility ensures that:
- People with disabilities can access your content
- Your site works across different devices and contexts
- You reach a wider audience
- You comply with legal requirements (ADA, WCAG)

## WCAG Guidelines

The Web Content Accessibility Guidelines provide four principles:

### 1. Perceivable
Information must be presentable to users in ways they can perceive:
- Provide text alternatives for images
- Offer captions for videos
- Ensure sufficient color contrast
- Make content adaptable to different presentations

### 2. Operable
User interface components must be operable:
- Make all functionality keyboard accessible
- Give users enough time to read content
- Don't use content that causes seizures
- Help users navigate and find content

### 3. Understandable
Content and operation must be understandable:
- Make text readable and understandable
- Make pages operate predictably
- Help users avoid and correct mistakes

### 4. Robust
Content must work with current and future technologies:
- Maximize compatibility with assistive technologies
- Use valid, semantic HTML
- Ensure proper ARIA usage

## Practical Implementation

### Semantic HTML
```html
<header>
  <nav aria-label="Main navigation">
    <!-- Navigation items -->
  </nav>
</header>

<main>
  <article>
    <h1>Article Title</h1>
    <!-- Content -->
  </article>
</main>

<footer>
  <!-- Footer content -->
</footer>
```

### ARIA Attributes
```html
<button aria-label="Close dialog" aria-expanded="false">
  ×
</button>
```

### Color Contrast
Ensure text meets WCAG AA standards:
- Normal text: 4.5:1 contrast ratio
- Large text: 3:1 contrast ratio

### Keyboard Navigation
Test your site using only the keyboard:
- Tab through all interactive elements
- Use Enter/Space to activate
- Ensure focus indicators are visible

## Testing Tools

Use these tools to check accessibility:
- Browser DevTools accessibility audits
- Screen readers (NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver)
- Automated testing tools (axe, WAVE)
- Manual keyboard testing

## Benefits Beyond Compliance

Accessible websites also benefit:
- SEO performance (search engines love semantic HTML)
- Mobile users (touch targets, readable text)
- Users in challenging contexts (bright sunlight, noisy environments)
- Older users with age-related impairments

## Continuous Improvement

Accessibility is an ongoing process:
- Test with real users who have disabilities
- Stay updated with WCAG guidelines
- Make accessibility part of your design process
- Train your team on accessibility principles

---

*Building a web that works for everyone.*]]></Value>
